{{Infobox Website |name = ''Node Magazine'' |logo = NodeMagazine.jpg |screenshot = |caption = Cover of the fictional magazine |url = http://www.nodemagazine.com/ |commercial = No |type = Annotator |language = [[English language|English]] |registration = No |owner = Sean Kearney<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whois.net/whois_new.cgi?d=nodemagazine&tld=com |title=Whois.Net |accessdate=2008-07-27 |work=[[WHOIS]] |publisher= |date= }}</ref> |author = patternBoy |launch date = February 7, 2007 |current status = |revenue = }} '''''Node Magazine''''' is a [[literature|literary]] project in the guise of a fictional magazine created to annotate the novel ''[[Spook Country]]'' by [[William Gibson]].
The project is essentially a [[hypertext]] version of the novel.<ref name="now romancer">{{cite web |url=http://www.salon.com/books/int/2007/08/11/william_gibson/index_np.html |title=Now Romancer |accessdate=2007-10-30 |last=Lim |first=Dennis |date=2007-08-11 |work=Salon Books |publisher=''[[Salon.com|Salon]]''}}</ref> It takes its name from ''Node'', a non-existent magazine in ''Spook Country'' owned by [[Hubertus Bigend]], which employs the novel's protagonist to pursue the source of [[locative art]].<ref name="broome">{{cite web|first=Kevin |last=Broome |url=http://www.kevinbroome.com/2007/09/william-gibson-at-cbc-book-club.html |title=William Gibson at the CBC Book Club |accessdate=2007-10-30 |work=broome: ideas&executions |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720181720/http://www.kevinbroome.com/2007/09/william-gibson-at-cbc-book-club.html |archivedate=July 20, 2008 }}</ref><ref name="scary">{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Watson |title=William Gibson explores the science fiction of the here-and-now in his new novel |url=http://www.santacruzsentinel.com/archive/2007/August/05/style/stories/05style.htm |work=Bookends |publisher=''[[Santa Cruz Sentinel]]'' |date=2007-08-05 |accessdate=2007-10-30 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930181430/http://www.santacruzsentinel.com/archive/2007/August/05/style/stories/05style.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-09-30}}</ref>
The project drew attention from the novelist,<ref name="silicon">{{cite web |url=http://networks.silicon.com/webwatch/0,39024667,39168006,00.htm |title= Q&A: William Gibson, science fiction novelist |accessdate=2007-10-30 |last=Ranger |first=Steve |date=2007-08-06 |publisher=Silicon.com}}</ref> and has been featured in ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'', ''[[Salon.com|Salon]]'', ''[[The Seattle Times]]'' and the ''[[Santa Cruz Sentinel]]''. The academic literary critic [[John Sutherland (author)|John Sutherland]] has claimed that the project threatened "to completely overhaul the way [[literary criticism]] is conducted".<ref name="node idea">{{cite news |first=John |last=Sutherland |authorlink=John Sutherland (author) |title=Node idea |url=http://books.guardian.co.uk/comment/story/0,,2159309,00.html?gusrc=rss&feed=10 |work=Comment |publisher=''[[The Guardian]]'' |date=2007-08-31 |accessdate=2007-10-30 }}</ref>
==Origin== The project was initiated when the recipient of an [[Advance copy|advanced reading copy]] of the novel mobilised "an army of volunteers" to track the references and assemble the cloud of [[metadata|data]] surrounding the novel – every element of the work which is searchable on internet resources such as [[Google]] and [[Wikipedia]].<ref name="node idea"/><ref name="seattle">{{cite news |first=Mary Ann |last=Gwinn |title=Futuristic fantasy lives now for author William Gibson |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/books/2003821831_gibson06.html?syndication=rss |work=Books |publisher=''[[The Seattle Times]]'' |date=2007-08-06 |accessdate=2007-10-30 }}</ref> The pseudonymous author, under the ''[[nom de plume]]'' patternBoy, conceived the Node project as "a multi-author blog of fictional news stories in the ''Spook Country'' universe", and did not anticipate that it would itself become the focus of media attention.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://node.tumblr.com/post/7987295 |title=And Now, Towards Chapter 85... |accessdate=2007-10-30 |work=Node tumblr }}</ref> He declared the launch of the Node [[tumblog]] sister-site to ''Node Magazine'' on June 24, 2007, with the following announcement:
{{quote|With 42 days before the official release and a total of 84 chapters, I will begin posting two short (under 807 characters each in celebration of the official release date) chapter summaries each day. Quotations will be very sparse and all posts will contain my interpretations (and likely significant spoilers) re: the yet-to-be-released work.<ref name="announce">{{cite web |url=http://node.tumblr.com/post/4195863 |title=Countdown begins: 42 days, 84 chapters |accessdate=2007-10-30 |date=2007-06-24 |work=Node tumblog |publisher=}}</ref>}}
The project has precedent in Joe Clark's [http://fawny.org/pr/ PR-Otaku], an attempt at logging and annotating Gibson's preceding novel ''[[Pattern Recognition (novel)|Pattern Recognition]]''.<ref name="pr-otaku">{{cite web|url=http://nodemagazine.com/2007/08/17/no-offense-intended/ |title=No Offense Intended… |accessdate=2007-10-30 |work=Node Magazine |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907125417/http://nodemagazine.com/2007/08/17/no-offense-intended/ |archivedate=September 7, 2008 }}</ref> Gibson has noted that while PR-Otaku "took a couple of years to come together", ''Node'' was complete before the novel was even published.<ref name="wapo">{{cite news |first=Joel |last=Garreau |author2=Meg Smith |title=Through the Looking Glass |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/09/05/AR2007090502582_pf.html |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=2007-09-06 |accessdate=2007-10-30 }}</ref>
==Significance== Sutherland credits the project as "giving an extraordinary reading of [the] novel in which everything is concretized – solidity and specification is added to [the] text."<ref name="sflondon">{{cite interview | last = Gibson | first = William | subjectlink = William Gibson | interviewer = [[John Sutherland (author)|John Sutherland]] | url = http://www.sci-fi-london.com/tv/channel/18 | work = [[Sci-Fi-London]] | publisher = SCI-FI-LONDON.TV | location = [[London]] | date = 2007-08-28 | accessdate = 2007-10-30 }} </ref> He has conceived this as nothing less than a new form of hyper-[[annotation]]:
{{quote|What the unknown Node-maestro has done is poles apart…[h]e's channelled the raw material supplied by his volunteers into a sign-posted route through ''Spook Country.'' It opens the way, I believe, to a new kind of critical commentary on texts. One can see, easily enough, how it could be extended to ''[[Paradise Lost]],'' or ''[[Hamlet]].''<ref name="node idea"/>}}
Gibson in turn has characterized the project as "a sort of little Wikipedia" for ''Spook Country,''<ref name="silicon"/> and has declared it to be "stunning," remarkably accurate, genuinely novel and "sort of scary."<ref name="now romancer"/><ref name="scary"/><ref name="sflondon"/> He has spoken of his newfound awareness when writing of "a ghostly cloud of [[hypertext]] hanging around the text of the manuscript," the alteration this has on the way readers experience the text, and the fact that all his research will be retraceable by readers of his work.<ref name="sflondon"/>
